/PL815/XXREADINGS: NEW YEARòS DAY/XX/PR

/KANEW YEARòS DAY/XX/PR

Each year should be the best year we have yet lived./PR

Each year we are more learned in the ways of life./PR

Each year we are wiser than the year before./PR

Each year our eyes know better the sights to seek./PR

Each year our ears listen with a finer tuning./PR

Every happening is a jewel, wrought about the fancy of time./PR

All that we understand of the universe is the setting for each/PR


sight and sound of day./PR

The child looks with gladness each year to be one year older./PR

Should not this welcome pursue us all our years?/PR

The piling of the years is a richness like the piling of gold./PR

Our years are coins with which we can purchase more wisely at/PR


the bazaars of each new season./PR

Our love is more pliant and patient having been taught by time./PR

This New Year is one year older than the last./PR

The earth is more abounding in its growth./PR

The creatures have moved another step in their unfolding./PR

Humankind has left us one more year of art for our/PR


contemplation./PR

History is one year more resonant with lessons./PR

The sunrises are one year more familiar and promising./PR

The sunsets are one year less fearful, and the peace of the night/PR


is one year closer./PR

Kenneth L. Patton/XX/PR

